<span id="freeTextContainer6644431993368307945">I didn&apos;t think DFW would live up to the hype either. I can&apos;t remember how I came across it, but I was first formally introduced to Wallace via his Boo</span>
  <span id="freeText6644431993368307945" style="display:none">I didn't think DFW would live up to the hype either. I can't remember how I came across it, but I was first formally introduced to Wallace via his BookTV interview five years after Jest was published. I normally find interviews with writers -- or maybe just anyone -- to be rather droll, but Dave seemed particularly thoughtful and creative. I wanted to experience his work. <br /><br />Then, after a bit of research, I remembered my father telling me about Infinite Jest when I was a boy of maybe seven or eight. He was explaining it as he set up for VCR. That's what fueled me to borrow my roommate's mammoth paperback edition, and I was not disappointed. It's one of two books to make me laugh out loud -- the second being the near-equal genius of American Psycho.<br /><br />You explained it well, my friend, and I doubt it's any accident your review is nostalgic of Wallace's writing style. Over two decades have gone by and still nobody has created more neologisms or gotten away with such a blatant footnote fetish, or so I have found.</span>
  <a data-text-id="6644431993368307945" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

